04624nmm a2200661Ia 9781501703737DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979911497  a97815017037377 a10.7591/97815017037372doi  a(DE-B1597)478413  a(OCoLC)936693225  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a338.4/7663200904223/eng1 aItçaina, Xabier, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVarietals of Capitalism :bA Political Economy of the Changing Wine Industry /cXabier Itçaina, Antoine Roger, Andy Smith. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b7 line figures, 9 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Political Economy0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVarietals of Capitalism shows that politics is an omnipresent part of the economics of wine and of economic activity in general. Based on a four-year research project encompassing fieldwork in France, Spain, Italy, and Romania, Xabier Itçaina, Antoine Roger, and Andy Smith examine the causes and effects of a radical reform adopted at the EU level in 2008. Regulatory change politically transformed the rationale of EU support to the wine industry, from shaping the supply side to encouraging producers to adapt to the demands of a supposedly "new consumer."To explain the adoption and impact of the reform, the authors develop an analytical framework to capture the actors—their perceptions, preferences, and interdependencies—within an industry crisscrossed by institutions located at the global, European, national, and local scales. This framework combines concepts and lessons from historical institutionalism and regulationist economics, Bourdieu's field theory, and the sociology of public policymaking. The authors reject accounts that attribute policy change simply to material determinants and "the invisible hand of the market." They emphasize the crucial importance of institutions within sectors of the economy, and propose ways to bolster constructivist approaches to political economy by linking industrial change to scientific and bureaucratic balances of power. This book’s novel focus on different levels of institutional impact should prove influential in the study of the politics of industry, and more broadly within the comparative analysis of capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aFood Studies. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  aCapitalism, politics, economics of wine, wine industry, EU reform, EU support to the wine industry, European winde industry.1 aRoger, Antoine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSmith, Andy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2016z9783110485332oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170373740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501703737423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501703737/original  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DSWb2016